1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,719
Well, let's start right away. The title of this deep dive, brain drain, a harm,

2
00:00:05,719 --> 00:00:11,240
raises a fundamental question. Today, we explore a natural and historical experiment,

3
00:00:11,240 --> 00:00:13,919
and I must say, an absolutely fascinating one.

4
00:00:13,919 --> 00:00:18,039
It concerns the immigration of highly specialized figures.

5
00:00:18,039 --> 00:00:23,000
We will dig deep into how knowledge production and scientific progress

6
00:00:23,000 --> 00:00:25,600
react to supply shocks.

7
00:00:25,600 --> 00:00:30,040
Here is our path. We will start from the division during the Cold War.

8
00:00:30,040 --> 00:00:35,020
We will go through Soviet isolation and the Luzin affair, then arrive at the collapse

9
00:00:35,020 --> 00:00:40,000
of the Wall and the subsequent exodus. After that, we will analyze the shockwave on local

10
00:00:40,000 --> 00:00:42,719
talents, the collapse of their productivity.

11
00:00:42,719 --> 00:00:48,000
And to conclude, we will take a look at what we will call the global mathematical cake.

12
00:00:48,000 --> 00:00:53,560
Point 1, the division of the Cold War. To truly understand the impact of all this,

13
00:00:53,560 --> 00:00:58,520
we must take a step back and frame the geopolitical climate of the time. There existed

14
00:00:58,520 --> 00:01:04,000
literally two parallel worlds. Isaac Newton said, "If I have seen further, it is because

15
00:01:04,000 --> 00:01:08,560
I stood on the shoulders of giants." This phrase captures the beating heart of

16
00:01:08,560 --> 00:01:14,000
research. Creating knowledge is not a job for lone wolves; it is an ultra-social process

17
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:19,719
based on exchange. A researcher's ideas feed on those of others, and vice versa.

18
00:01:19,719 --> 00:01:25,599
But what happens if this vital flow is cut off cleanly by absolutely

19
00:01:25,599 --> 00:01:32,239
impenetrable political borders? Let's move to the second point. The isolation and the Luzin affair. The answer lies precisely

20
00:01:32,239 --> 00:01:37,599
in history; a total isolation of the Soviet scientific community from the rest

21
00:01:37,599 --> 00:01:43,200
of the planet was created, giving life to a mathematical ecosystem that stood on its own. We start, obviously,

22
00:01:43,200 --> 00:01:49,680
from the foundation of the USSR, but the true turning point comes in 1936 with the Luzin affair. Nikolai

23
00:01:49,680 --> 00:01:55,040
Luzin was a leading mathematician of the Academy of Sciences and underwent a heavy

24
00:01:55,040 --> 00:02:00,120
defamatory campaign; they even accused him of sending his best discoveries to foreign journals,

25
00:02:00,120 --> 00:02:04,879
a true political crime at the time. The result: from that day on, Soviet mathematicians

26
00:02:04,879 --> 00:02:10,800
were locked down; they had to publish almost exclusively in Russian and in internal journals. Mail

27
00:02:10,800 --> 00:02:15,840
with the West was controlled, trips abroad were banned—in short, the Iron Curtain

28
00:02:15,840 --> 00:02:21,719
had heavily fallen on mathematics as well. And what happens after decades of total closure?

29
00:02:21,719 --> 00:02:28,000
Two completely different mathematical dialects are formed. Separated from everything, the two blocks

30
00:02:28,000 --> 00:02:34,320
specialized in totally different fields, driven by their specific histories and government funds.

31
00:02:34,320 --> 00:02:40,040
The Americans were unbeatable in areas like statistics, operations research, and computer science.

32
00:02:40,039 --> 00:02:45,959
The Soviets, on the other hand, reigned supreme in differential equations. There is an almost

33
00:02:45,959 --> 00:02:51,799
tragicomic detail in all this: in the Soviet Union, dealing with statistics could literally be

34
00:02:51,799 --> 00:02:57,159
dangerous. Why? Because it involved handling state data, and it wasn't exactly wise to

35
00:02:57,159 --> 00:03:03,479
nose around too much in government affairs. The data of the time show very clearly

36
00:03:03,479 --> 00:03:09,199
how clear this division was. Before the 90s, there were entire sectors of excellence

37
00:03:09,199 --> 00:03:15,200
for Americans in which the Soviets simply published nothing. No one expected a

38
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:20,440
change anytime soon; even in the late 80s, it was believed that the Soviet system was

39
00:03:20,440 --> 00:03:25,960
rock-solid and that this isolation would go on for entire generations. Which brings us

40
00:03:25,960 --> 00:03:32,060
to point 3, the collapse and the exodus. As we know, history has its plot twists. These two

41
00:03:32,060 --> 00:03:38,920
universes, isolated for half a century, suddenly collided. Over a thousand. This impressive number

42
00:03:38,920 --> 00:03:43,840
represents the scale of the exodus. With the collapse of the Soviet Union, more than

43
00:03:43,840 --> 00:03:48,840
a thousand brilliant minds found themselves catapulted into the global academic market. Of these,

44
00:03:48,840 --> 00:03:54,320
336 elite mathematicians landed directly in the United States. We are talking about an intellectual supply

45
00:03:54,320 --> 00:03:59,360
shock without any precedent in recent history. To grasp the essence of

46
00:03:59,360 --> 00:04:05,160
this earthquake, we must make a distinction between tacit knowledge and codified knowledge.

47
00:04:05,719 --> 00:04:10,599
During the Cold War, Soviet journals were translated into English anyway, so

48
00:04:10,599 --> 00:04:15,599
the codified knowledge was there, the texts were there. But the real turning point was

49
00:04:15,599 --> 00:04:21,120
the unlocking of tacit knowledge. This is the unwritten genius that lives in human

50
00:04:21,120 --> 00:04:25,959
capital, in the minds of people. It is what is passed on by chatting at the

51
00:04:25,959 --> 00:04:30,800
coffee machine or reasoning together in front of a blackboard without any bureaucratic obstacle.

52
00:04:31,360 --> 00:04:36,840
There is an anecdote from Harvard that perfectly summarizes the situation. Persi Diaconis, a very famous

53
00:04:36,840 --> 00:04:42,360
American mathematician, had been banging his head against a problem for twenty years. Twenty. He had asked

54
00:04:42,360 --> 00:04:48,000
half of North America for help, but zero, total darkness. Then the Soviet visitors arrive; he

55
00:04:48,000 --> 00:04:54,120
explains the problem to Dr. Reshetikhin, and magic. The solution arrives almost instantaneously.

56
00:04:54,120 --> 00:04:58,639
The Soviets had chewed over that kind of problem for years. Suddenly the door had opened

57
00:04:58,639 --> 00:05:04,159
to a whole new world of fresh insights. This led to an incredible surge

58
00:05:04,159 --> 00:05:10,079
in co-authorships, that is, joint publications between Soviets and Americans. Before

59
00:05:10,079 --> 00:05:16,959
1990, collaborations grazed absolute zero. Immediately after, they exploded. The invisible

60
00:05:16,959 --> 00:05:22,279
barrier had finally collapsed, leaving room for a literally exciting flow of ideas.

61
00:05:22,760 --> 00:05:29,480
And here we come to point 4, the shockwave on the natives. Be careful, though, because it is not all

62
00:05:29,480 --> 00:05:35,040
gold that glitters. The arrival of an avalanche of brains of this caliber didn't just spread

63
00:05:35,040 --> 00:05:41,920
beautiful ideas, it also sparked ruthless competition. It's the famous crowd-out or displacement effect.

64
00:05:41,920 --> 00:05:47,400
Academia is not an infinite space. Tenure-track positions are limited, research

65
00:05:47,400 --> 00:05:52,120
funds have a cap, and the space to get published in prestigious journals is

66
00:05:52,120 --> 00:05:58,040
limited; putting so many superstars on the market means that someone inevitably loses their

67
00:05:58,040 --> 00:06:04,280
seat. And in fact, analyzing unemployment rates in the early 90s, an

68
00:06:04,280 --> 00:06:09,879
absolutely anomalous peak emerges. For new mathematics PhDs in North America, unemployment

69
00:06:09,879 --> 00:06:16,840
reached a frightening record of 12% in 1991. Just at the exact moment Soviet geniuses

70
00:06:16,840 --> 00:06:21,959
arrived on American shores, young local talents found themselves facing a barrier.

71
00:06:22,359 --> 00:06:28,519
Let's move to point 5, the collapse of productivity. It's not just that the shockwave hit new

72
00:06:28,519 --> 00:06:34,279
graduates. The numbers are ruthless. And they tell us that even American mathematicians, already well established in the

73
00:06:34,279 --> 00:06:40,679
system, suffered a very hard blow. The arriving Soviets were subject to an extreme positive

74
00:06:40,679 --> 00:06:48,120
selection; they were literally the top of the top. After 1992, the average for an American was

75
00:06:48,120 --> 00:06:54,040
almost seven published articles, with about 52 citations. The average for a Soviet emigrant

76
00:06:54,040 --> 00:07:01,079
was over 27 articles and as many as 209 citations. They were machines. We are talking about the intellectual elite of a

77
00:07:01,079 --> 00:07:05,720
global superpower, working at a pace that was simply unsustainable for most

78
00:07:05,720 --> 00:07:12,280
US colleagues. Of course, not everyone suffered in the same way. The decline in productivity

79
00:07:12,360 --> 00:07:18,760
was very steep, but specifically for those Americans who dealt with the exact same topics

80
00:07:18,760 --> 00:07:24,440
as the Soviets. Those who studied statistics could sleep soundly; the Soviets weren't really interested,

81
00:07:24,440 --> 00:07:30,120
but those who studied differential equations? Well, they encountered a real blockage. Their

82
00:07:30,120 --> 00:07:36,520
productivity plummeted. And there is more. These mathematicians exposed to competition not only

83
00:07:36,520 --> 00:07:41,960
published less, but also lost resonance. Their probability of scoring a so-called

84
00:07:41,960 --> 00:07:47,320
"home run," that is, one of those historic, incredibly cited articles that change the face of a

85
00:07:47,320 --> 00:07:53,720
discipline, plummeted by over 20%. Their work was irremediably overshadowed

86
00:07:53,720 --> 00:08:00,680
by the exceptional quality brought by the newcomers. Finally, point 6, the global mathematical cake,

87
00:08:00,680 --> 00:08:06,360
summing up, one wonders: did global mathematical knowledge gain from it,

88
00:08:06,360 --> 00:08:11,600
or did it simply shift from one hand to another? Summarizing the research, three

89
00:08:11,600 --> 00:08:17,160
key points emerge. First, highly exposed local scholars saw their productivity collapse.

90
00:08:17,160 --> 00:08:23,000
Second, this gap was perfectly filled by the Soviets. Third, and this is perhaps the

91
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:27,800
most surprising part, there is no evidence that the overall size of the mathematical knowledge

92
00:08:27,800 --> 00:08:32,759
cake increased tangibly. In short, it was an even swap.

93
00:08:32,759 --> 00:08:37,759
New talent replaced the old, but without launching a new golden age for

94
00:08:37,759 --> 00:08:43,159
the entire American discipline. There is, however, a small, enlightening exception, a

95
00:08:43,159 --> 00:08:50,159
tiny niche of exposed Americans, barely 2.8%, who made a different choice. Instead of

96
00:08:50,159 --> 00:08:56,240
suffering from the competition, they decided to integrate it. They worked side by side and co-authored

97
00:08:56,240 --> 00:09:02,000
research with the emigrants. And guess what: for this restricted group, the drop in performance

98
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:07,759
never happened. Joining the new wave proved to be the only true antidote to survive the

99
00:09:07,759 --> 00:09:14,679
displacement. All this leaves us with a huge question. When the doors open and a wave of

100
00:09:14,679 --> 00:09:20,120
superstars floods the market, the resulting dynamics are complex, counter-intuitive, and

101
00:09:20,120 --> 00:09:25,679
so the final question remains: does the massive entry of geniuses into a system really act as an absolute accelerator

102
00:09:25,679 --> 00:09:31,120
for global progress, or do the bottlenecks and limited resources of the academic world simply end up

103
00:09:31,120 --> 00:09:35,919
replacing the talent that was there before? It is a deep enigma and, I would say,

104
00:09:35,919 --> 00:09:39,480
extraordinarily relevant. To all of us, much to think about.